The basic logic is that trees capture and store carbon dioxide, which is go=
od for the environment. This means that cutting down a tree is worse for th=
e environment than not cutting down that tree, and planting a tree is bette=
r for the environment than not planting that tree.
  [3]
 And then, when you are evaluating the environmental impact of some person =
or project or company, you have important questions of baselines:
=09If a company does not chop down trees, is that just a neutral fact (it c=
hanges nothing about the environment one way or the other), or a=C2=A0posit=
ive=C2=A0fact (it=C2=A0could have=C2=A0chopped down trees, but didn=E2=80=
=99t)? Or for that matter a negative=C2=A0fact (it could have=C2=A0planted =
trees, but didn=E2=80=99t)?=C2=A0What is the carbon=C2=A0benefit of not cho=
pping down trees? How many trees did you not chop down?=C2=A0Everyone in th=
e world who is not currently engaged in chopping down a tree is not choppin=
g down any of the billions of trees in the world, but they can=E2=80=99t al=
l get credit for conserving billions of trees.=09If a company=C2=A0does=C2=
=A0chop down trees, is that a bad fact (chopping down trees) or a good fact=
 (not chopping down=C2=A0other=C2=A0trees)? Even if you are chopping down t=
rees,=C2=A0how many trees did you not chop down?=C2=A0Everyone in the world=
 who=C2=A0is=C2=A0currently engaged in chopping down a tree is not chopping=
 down any of the billions of=C2=A0other=C2=A0trees in the world.

I realize all of this is sort of dumb and juvenile but here is  the Wall St=
reet Journal on Weyerhaeuser:

Weyerhaeuser Co. has cut down more trees than any other American company si=
nce its founder started logging before the Civil War. Environmentalists hav=
e long treated it as an enemy.
Now, the new math of carbon emissions is enabling the lumber producer to ca=
st itself as something quite different: a force for environmental good.
Its 10.6 million acres of U.S. timberland act as a giant sponge for carbon =
dioxide, which Weyerhaeuser says more than compensates for the greenhouse g=
ases it emits by felling trees, sawing them into lumber and distributing wo=
od products.
Although Weyerhaeuser is cutting down as many trees as ever and plans to in=
crease lumber production 5% in the next few years, it says its net carbon f=
ootprint is negative=E2=80=94so much so that it is offering carbon dioxide =
storage capacity to other companies. Weyerhaeuser expects a new unit dedica=
ted to helping other firms offset their emissions to generate $100 million =
a year in profit by the end of 2025. =E2=80=A6
Weyerhaeuser is America=E2=80=99s largest private landowner. Its timberland=
s range from expanses of Douglas fir in the Pacific Northwest to pine plant=
ations across the South to the North Maine Woods. Altogether, its trees cov=
er an area roughly twice the size of New Jersey.
Weyerhaeuser says those trees remove about 14 million metric tons of carbon=
 dioxide from the atmosphere each year. It says an additional 10 million me=
tric tons are held in timberlands owned by others that supply its mills, an=
d in the logs it sells to others.

Yes! Sure! If you buy a million acres of forest and don=E2=80=99t chop down=
 the trees, then you are =E2=80=94=C2=A0relative to some baseline =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0improving the environment and capturing carbon and you can sell carbo=
n credits.
  [4]
 If you buy a million acres of forest and=C2=A0do=C2=A0chop down the trees,=
 as long as you don=E2=80=99t chop them down all at once,=C2=A0then you are=
 still, relative to=C2=A0some=C2=A0baseline, improving the environment and =
capturing carbon and you can sell carbon credits. Why not!
Even if you do chop down all of the trees, there is still carbon in the tre=
es you chopped down, so relative to some baseline you are still capturing c=
arbon and can sell carbon credits:

Weyerhaeuser produces about 950,000 miles of lumber a year and more than en=
ough wood panels to cover Manhattan four sheets thick. Even though lumber d=
oesn=E2=80=99t continue absorbing carbon dioxide, the company takes credit =
for an additional 11 million tons of carbon held in those wood products. It=
 reasons that carbon continues to be stored in the lumber after it goes int=
o houses and other structures, which wouldn=E2=80=99t be the case if a tree=
 fell and decayed on the forest floor.
Taking credit for carbon in harvested wood, manufactured products and on ti=
mberlands owned by others is inconsistent with guidelines other companies u=
se for their emissions accounting. Ara Erickson, Weyerhaeuser=E2=80=99s vic=
e president of corporate sustainability, said the company is pushing its ca=
se with the organizations that set carbon standards.=C2=A0

Yes! A tree in the forest captures carbon, but it might fall and decay and =
release that carbon! Better cut it down quickly to prevent that!

