 =20

I guess this is the glass-half-full   way to put it:

Crypto exchange Coinbase Global Inc. may consider moving its headquarters o=
utside the US unless the country changes its approach to regulation, Chief =
Executive Officer Brian Armstrong said.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CAnything is on the table,=E2=80=9D Armstrong said when asked by fo=
rmer UK Chancellor of the Exchequer George Osborne at a fintech conference =
in London on Tuesday whether San Francisco-based Coinbase would consider mo=
ving to Britain. =E2=80=9CIncluding, you know, relocating or whatever is ne=
cessary.=E2=80=9D
While Armstrong has been vocal about his opposition to current US crypto re=
gulation, raising the possibility of relocating marks an escalation of the =
rhetoric. ...
=E2=80=9CThe US has the potential to be an important market in crypto, but =
right now, we are not seeing that regulatory clarity needed,=E2=80=9D Armst=
rong said, adding that the UK is Coinbase=E2=80=99s second largest market g=
lobally by revenue. =E2=80=9CI think if a number of years go by where we do=
n=E2=80=99t see regulatory clarity emerge in the US, we may have to conside=
r investing more in other regions of the world.=E2=80=9D

=E2=80=9CRegulatory clarity=E2=80=9D is largely a euphemism, though there i=
s some literal truth to it. I think it is crystal, crystal, crystal clear t=
hat:
=09the US Securities and Exchange Commission believes that most crypto toke=
ns are securities and that Coinbase is breaking the law by operating as sec=
urities exchange that is not registered with the SEC;=09the SEC is going to=
 bring more lawsuits, including probably one against Coinbase, saying that;=
=09the SEC has a pretty strong case under basic, long-established US securi=
ties law; and=09the SEC=E2=80=99s answer to Coinbase=E2=80=99s question of =
=E2=80=9Cokay well how do we comply with the law and operate a US crypto ex=
change that=C2=A0is=C2=A0registered with the SEC?=E2=80=9D is =E2=80=9Chaha=
ha you don=E2=80=99t, get outta here, enjoy England.=E2=80=9D

We have   talked about   this a   lot. These are answers that Coinbase   do=
esn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0like, for obvious reasons, and they are also answers tha=
t the SEC   doesn=E2=80=99t always come out and say directly, but they are =
nonetheless very clear.
That said there are some uncertainties:
=09When is the SEC going to bring a case against Coinbase, and exactly what=
 will it say?=09Will it win in court on its arguments that basically all cr=
ypto tokens are securities? Again I think the case is quite strong, but the=
re do seem to be crypto lawyers who disagree with me =E2=80=94=C2=A0includi=
ng at Coinbase =E2=80=94=C2=A0and eventually judges will decide and there i=
s always some uncertainty there.

But the biggest uncertainty is, like,=C2=A0is this it? Is the SEC=E2=80=99s=
 current posture the final answer on US crypto regulation? If we assume tha=
t the SEC is going to be maximally aggressive about, not =E2=80=9Cregulatin=
g=E2=80=9D crypto, but=C2=A0cracking down=C2=A0on crypto, and if we assume =
that the SEC will win in court because it has a pretty strong case under ex=
isting law, then the basic path for crypto in the US is =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=
=99s going to be more or less illegal to raise money for a crypto project, =
or to offer a new crypto token widely, or to operate a crypto exchange that=
 trades anything other than Bitcoin and Ether.=E2=80=9D It will take some t=
ime to get there, since the SEC moves kinda slowly and the courts move even=
 more slowly and crypto people seem very committed to this bit of complaini=
ng about =E2=80=9Cregulatory uncertainty=E2=80=9D rather than =E2=80=9Cthe =
regulators are clearly and fully committed to stamping us out.=E2=80=9D But=
 the long-term path that we are currently on is pretty clear.
So the uncertainty is,=C2=A0will anything about the law or the political si=
tuation change? Will  Congress step in and say to the SEC, =E2=80=9Cnah you=
 can=E2=80=99t fully stamp out crypto=E2=80=9D? Will a presidential electio=
n bring a new head of the SEC who will say =E2=80=9Cehh actually crypto is =
fine, go ahead=E2=80=9D? These outcomes all seem=C2=A0possible; the fact th=
at Europe seems more welcoming to crypto than the US suggests that there is=
 nothing inevitable about the US crackdown. But, again, the political situa=
tion for crypto right now seems bad; Coinbase=E2=80=99s argument that the S=
EC is stifling innovation is less appealing after last year=E2=80=99s crypt=
o meltdown, where much of the innovation in crypto once again turned out to=
 be new ways to steal money from customers.=C2=A0

