<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Blank checks</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Most US public corporations are mostly control=
led by their boards of directors, who sort of loosely answer to the shareho=
lders.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color:=
 transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> The shareholders get to vote to re-elect the directors every year, but=
 the directors generally run unopposed, serve as long as they want=C2=A0and=
 choose their own successors. And most big corporate decisions are made by =
the directors, or by the executives they appoint and supervise; the shareho=
lders only rarely get a vote on those decisions.<a class=3D"footnote-index"=
 href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display:=
 inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> The shareholders are in some loose sense the owners of the corporation=
, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31207070.258=
446/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMjc=
vZXh4b24tbG9zdC1hLWNsaW1hdGUtcHJveHktZmlnaHQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQxODIzX01PTkVZU1=
RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwN=
DE4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB709c69a9" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">  in some loose sense</a> they get to supervise the directors, but in m=
ost practical senses, most of the time, the directors are in charge and the=
 shareholders are pretty much along for the ride.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not always, though. Some companies have contro=
lling shareholders who do have the practical power to remove directors. Som=
etimes an activist will buy a big stake in a company, run a proxy fight, an=
d try to get its own proposed directors elected instead of the incumbents. =
And some corporate decisions do have to be ratified by a shareholder vote. =
Most notably, the decision to sell the company requires a shareholder vote,=
 and the decision to=C2=A0<em>authorize=C2=A0</em>new shares =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0to let the board issue more shares than are currently authorized in the =
corporate charter =E2=80=94=C2=A0also requires the approval of a majority o=
f the shares.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But at most public companies these situations =
are rare enough that, when they do arise, the board=C2=A0<em>and also the s=
hareholders </em>can find them kind of annoying. If you are a director at a=
 public company who has been used to having collegial quarterly meetings wi=
th the other directors, getting reports from a chief executive officer whom=
 you like and admire, guiding the company=E2=80=99s pursuit of a strategy t=
hat you believe in, and selecting new directors to improve the board=E2=80=
=99s expertise while maintaining its effectiveness and collegiality =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0you might be annoyed when someone shows up and says =E2=80=9CI=E2=
=80=99m gonna fire all of you and take the company in a different direction=
=E2=80=9D just because they happen to own a bunch of stock. Who put them in=
 charge? Why do they think that just=C2=A0<em>buying some stock=C2=A0</em>g=
ives them the right to manage the company?=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or if you are a director at a company in some =
financial trouble, you might have a series of difficult and thoughtful boar=
d meetings at which you all agree, based on a great deal of analysis and so=
ul-searching, that the only way to solve the company=E2=80=99s troubles is =
to sell a lot more stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0more stock, as it happens, than is =
authorized by the charter. And you might be annoyed to have to go out and m=
ake the case to underinformed retail shareholders that they should vote to =
approve new shares. =E2=80=9CWhat about dilution,=E2=80=9D they will ask, a=
nd you will roll your eyes and say =E2=80=9Cyes we discussed this in some d=
etail and we already decided that this is what=E2=80=99s best for sharehold=
ers, just vote for it.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also though those retail shareholders themselv=
es might not bother to vote on anything, because their vote so rarely matte=
rs that the share ownership system is not really set up to make voting easy=
 and practical for them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Most US public corporations also have =E2=80=
=9Cblank-check preferred stock,=E2=80=9D which means that their charter aut=
horizes the board of directors to issue shares of preferred stock with any =
terms that the directors want. And there has been a fun small recent trend =
of boards of directors making novel use of blank-check preferred to, as it =
were,=C2=A0<em>fix=C2=A0</em>shareholder voting, to soften the shareholder =
voting requirements and make shareholder votes go the way the boards want.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This was kicked off last year by AMC Entertain=
ment Holdings Inc.=E2=80=99s APEs. AMC was a meme stock, it needed money, i=
t got money by selling stock, it ran out of authorized shares, and its larg=
ely retail shareholder base wouldn=E2=80=99t approve more. So AMC=E2=80=99s=
 board used its ability to issue blank-check preferred stock to <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31207070.258446/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjMvYW1jLWdvZXMtYXBl=
P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MTgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1=
uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDQxOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBc3b0d058" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  issue APEs</a>, which are preferred-s=
tock units that are meant to be equivalent to common stock. This got around=
 the shareholder voting requirement in two ways. First, if APEs are more or=
 less equivalent to common stock, then the board could issue more common-st=
ock-equivalents=C2=A0<em>without </em>a shareholder vote: It could go to in=
vestors and say =E2=80=9Cwe have some APEs, they=E2=80=99re just as good as=
 common stock,=E2=80=9D and sell them to raise money. Second, if APEs are=
=C2=A0<em>not </em>just as good as common stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0and they hav=
e traded at a big discount to the common =E2=80=94=C2=A0then at least they=
=C2=A0<em>vote=C2=A0</em>like common stock, and the board can go out and as=
k all shareholders (common and APE) to authorize new common shares. The boa=
rd did that, and also, uh, optimized that vote: It <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31207070.258446/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDEvYW1jLWhhcy1zb21lLWNsZXZlci1hc=
GVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MTgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJj=
ZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDQxOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4166179d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  structured the APEs</a> so that ev=
en APEs that didn=E2=80=99t vote were=C2=A0<em>counted=C2=A0</em>as voting,=
 to make it easier to get a majority of all shares; it also <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31207070.258446/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMjIvZnR4LWZyaWVuZHMtZmxp=
cC1vbi1zYmY_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQxODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1=
fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNDE4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dW=
Zm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB99f3684c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  placed a big block of APEs<=
/a> with a friendly investor who agreed to vote to authorize more shares.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">AMC=E2=80=99s basic theory here was that its s=
hareholders (1) <em>should </em>want to authorize more shares (to avoid fin=
ancial distress, etc.) and also (2)=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>want to authorize=
 more shares: It=E2=80=99s just that they are overwhelmingly retail investo=
rs, and retail investors mostly don=E2=80=99t vote even for things that the=
y want. But some shareholders don=E2=80=99t like it; <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31207070.258446/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMjEvYW1jLWFwZXMtaGF0ZS1hbWMtcy1=
hcGVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MTgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdX=
JjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDQxOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB46961904" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  they sued</a>, AMC held the vote=
, AMC basically <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31=
207070.258446/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwM=
jMtMDMtMTUvc2lsaWNvbi12YWxsZXktYmFuay1pcy1mb3Itc2FsZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDE4MjNf=
TU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGV=
ybT0yMzA0MTgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9a720=
30b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  won the vote</a>, the shareholders and AMC came to a settlem=
ent agreement, but the court has <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/31207070.258446/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMTAvZnR4LWxvc3QtdHJhY2stb2YtaXRzLW1vbmV5P2NtcGlkPUJ=
CRDA0MTgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dG=
VyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDQxOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cBe3e7f50f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">  not yet signed off on it</a> and <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31207070.258446/aHR0cHM6Ly9uZXdzL=
mJsb29tYmVyZ2xhdy5jb20vZXNnL2FtYy1zaGFyZWhvbGRlcnMtd3JpdGUtaW4tZHJvdmVzLXVy=
Z2luZy1qdWRnZS10by1yZWplY3QtYXBlLWRlYWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB09d33c24" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> some shareholders have objected</a>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the <em>legality=C2=A0</em>of the APEs is s=
till unclear. On the one hand, the board of directors of AMC=C2=A0<em>does=
=C2=A0</em>have the blank-check power to issue new preferred stock with wha=
tever terms it wants; by the letter of the law and the charter the APEs see=
m fine. And the board=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>seem to have done this for go=
od, loyal, acting-in-the-best-interests-of-the-company reasons: It consider=
ed AMC=E2=80=99s financial situation, decided that raising more money by se=
lling stock was the right move, and concluded that the APEs were the best w=
ay to achieve that goal. On the other hand, though, it seems clear that the=
 board=C2=A0<em>was=C2=A0</em>trying to get around the requirement that its=
 shareholders vote to authorize new shares: The directors really were riggi=
ng the vote to achieve a result that they (reasonably, loyally, thoughtfull=
y) wanted. And rigging the shareholder vote to get the directors=E2=80=99 p=
referred outcome =E2=80=94=C2=A0even if the directors=E2=80=99 preference i=
s=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0seems like a tough thing for a cou=
rt to endorse.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the APEs inspired copycats. We have <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31207070.258446/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMTYvdGhlLXNlYy1=
jb21lcy1mb3ItY3J5cHRvLWN1c3RvZHk_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQxODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX2=
1lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNDE4JnV0bV9jY=
W1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB10996499" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked=
 about Soligenix Inc.</a>, a micro-cap biotech company that needed sharehol=
der approval to do a reverse stock split to remain listed on the Nasdaq. It=
=E2=80=99s apparently hard for Soligenix to get its penny-stock retail hold=
ers to vote for anything, and it needed a majority of all of its shares to =
vote for the reverse split: Shares that don=E2=80=99t vote count as votes a=
gainst.=C2=A0So it issued a new blank-check preferred stock that give each =
shareholder an extra 1,000 votes per share. This new stock would be automat=
ically redeemed right around the time of the shareholder vote: Any shares t=
hat=C2=A0<em>voted=C2=A0</em>would be counted in the vote, and then redeeme=
d immediately afterwards; any shares that=C2=A0<em>didn=E2=80=99t vote=C2=
=A0</em>would be redeemed right before the votes were counted. The result i=
s that, at the exact moment of the shareholder vote, only shares that actua=
lly voted would be outstanding, so if most of them voted yes Soligenix woul=
d get its majority. The extra-voting preferred stock is a way to get around=
 the requirement that a majority of all outstanding shares have to vote for=
 the reverse split, for Soligenix as for AMC.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/31207070.258446/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMjgvYW1jLXMtYXBlcy1oYXZlLXRvLXdhaXQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQx=
ODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXR=
tX3Rlcm09MjMwNDE4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
2c6614e0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">  there is Tilray Brands Inc.</a>, a publicly traded cann=
abis company with a lot of retail investors that also needed shareholder ap=
proval to collapse a dual-class share structure and authorize new shares. I=
t created a new blank-check preferred stock and sold all of it to a friendl=
y buyer called Double Diamond Holdings Ltd. The preferred stock had super-v=
oting rights, but it had to vote in proportion to the common shares that ac=
tually vote: If=C2=A045% of the common voted=C2=A0yes and 5% voted=C2=A0no,=
=C2=A0then 90% of the super-voting preferred shares would vote yes. After t=
he vote, the preferred would automatically convert into common stock; again=
, the extra-voting preferred stock was a way around the requirement to get =
a majority of the common shares to vote. (It worked; <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31207070.258446/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdv=
di9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTczMTM0OC8wMDAxMTQwMzYxMjMwMTIxMTA=
vYnJoYzEwMDQ5ODk4XzhrLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4fdcc996" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Til=
ray got a majority</a>.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then there are Purple=E2=80=99s PRPLS. We =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31207070.258446/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMTUvcHVyc=
GxlLWlubm92YXRpb24tcy1wcnBscy1pbm5vdmF0aW9uP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MTgyM19NT05FWVNU=
VUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDQ=
xOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB29187599" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">  talked in February</a> about Purple Innovation Inc., a publicly trade=
d mattress company that is 45% owned by Coliseum Capital Management LLC. Pu=
rple=E2=80=99s board is mostly independent of Coliseum, though Coliseum=E2=
=80=99s managing partner is on the board. Last year Coliseum proposed to bu=
y the rest of Purple, and Purple=E2=80=99s board <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31207070.258446/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9B=
cmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE2NDM5NTMvMDAwMTIxMzkwMDIyMDU5MTQ3L2VhMTY2Mjc4ZXg=
5OS0xX3B1cnBsZS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4eec3cfa" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> formed a s=
pecial committee</a> that considered the proposal and turned it down, creat=
ing a poison pill to block Coliseum from buying more stock. In February, Co=
liseum launched a proxy fight, nominating five candidates to the seven-memb=
er board of directors. With 45% of the stock, Coliseum seemed likely to win=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So Purple=E2=80=99s board announced a new blan=
k-check preferred stock thing called PRPLS, Proportional Representation Pre=
ferred Linked Stock, which would give each shareholder 100 extra votes per =
share, and would make those votes=C2=A0<em>cumulative</em>, meaning that a =
shareholder with one share of stock (and 100 extra PRPLS votes) could give =
101 votes to each of seven candidates for the board of directors, or 707 vo=
tes to a single candidate, or any other combination. This would make it eas=
ier for the existing board to get at least three, and maybe four, of its ca=
ndidates elected to the board: All of the non-Coliseum shareholders could c=
oncentrate their voting on a few incumbent candidates and get them elected,=
 even though Coliseum has a near majority of the votes.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/31207070.258446/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fy=
dGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMjQvc29tZS1zcGFjcy1oYXZlLXNwYXJlLWNhc2g_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQ=
xODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdX=
RtX3Rlcm09MjMwNDE4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B24194986" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> Coliseum sued</a>, saying that the PRPLS were illegal b=
ecause they were =E2=80=9Cdesigned solely to prevent Coliseum from electing=
 its nominees and removing existing directors.=E2=80=9D Last week <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31207070.258446/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3N3aXJlLmNvbS9uZXdzL2hvbWUvMjAyMzA0MTMwMDU4MDcvZW4vUHVycGxl=
