<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Look at all the trees that they=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>chop=
 down</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic logic is that trees capture and stor=
e carbon dioxide, which is good for the environment. This means that cuttin=
g down a tree is worse for the environment than not cutting down that tree,=
 and planting a tree is better for the environment than not planting that t=
ree.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: t=
ransparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> And then, when you are evaluating the environmental impact of some per=
son or project or company, you have important questions of baselines:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If a company does not chop down trees,=
 is that just a neutral fact (it changes nothing about the environment one =
way or the other), or a=C2=A0positive=C2=A0fact (it=C2=A0<em>could have=C2=
=A0</em>chopped down trees, but didn=E2=80=99t)? Or for that matter a <em>n=
egative=C2=A0</em>fact (it could have=C2=A0<em>planted </em>trees, but didn=
=E2=80=99t)?=C2=A0What is the carbon=C2=A0<em>benefit </em>of not chopping =
down trees? <em>How many trees did you not chop down?</em>=C2=A0Everyone in=
 the world who is not currently engaged in chopping down a tree is not chop=
ping down any of the billions of trees in the world, but they can=E2=80=99t=
 all get credit for conserving billions of trees.</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">If a company=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>chop down trees, is th=
at a bad fact (chopping down trees) or a good fact (not chopping down=C2=A0=
<em>other=C2=A0</em>trees)? Even if you are chopping down trees,=C2=A0<em>h=
ow many trees did you not chop down?=C2=A0</em>Everyone in the world who=C2=
=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>currently engaged in chopping down a tree is not choppi=
ng down any of the billions of=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>trees in the world.=
</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I realize all of this is sort of dumb and juve=
nile but here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
1207070.258446/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy93ZXllcmhhZXVzZXItbG9n=
Z2luZy1jYXJib24tZW1pc3Npb25zLW9mZnNldC1tYXJrZXQtZW52aXJvbm1lbnQtNzY4NTBjMDE=
_bW9kPWl0cF93c2omcnU9eWFob28/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB24411c31" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> th=
e Wall Street Journal on Weyerhaeuser</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Weyerhaeuser Co. has cut down more trees than =
any other American company since its founder started logging before the Civ=
il War. Environmentalists have long treated it as an enemy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, the new math of carbon emissions is enabl=
ing the lumber producer to cast itself as something quite different: a forc=
e for environmental good.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Its 10.6 million acres of U.S. timberland act =
as a giant sponge for carbon dioxide, which Weyerhaeuser says more than com=
pensates for the greenhouse gases it emits by felling trees, sawing them in=
to lumber and distributing wood products.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Although Weyerhaeuser is cutting down as many =
trees as ever and plans to increase lumber production 5% in the next few ye=
ars, it says its net carbon footprint is negative=E2=80=94so much so that i=
t is offering carbon dioxide storage capacity to other companies. Weyerhaeu=
ser expects a new unit dedicated to helping other firms offset their emissi=
ons to generate $100 million a year in profit by the end of 2025. =E2=80=A6=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Weyerhaeuser is America=E2=80=99s largest priv=
ate landowner. Its timberlands range from expanses of Douglas fir in the Pa=
cific Northwest to pine plantations across the South to the North Maine Woo=
ds. Altogether, its trees cover an area roughly twice the size of New Jerse=
y.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Weyerhaeuser says those trees remove about 14 =
million metric tons of carbon dioxide from the atmosphere each year. It say=
s an additional 10 million metric tons are held in timberlands owned by oth=
ers that supply its mills, and in the logs it sells to others.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes! Sure! If you buy a million acres of fores=
t and don=E2=80=99t chop down the trees, then you are =E2=80=94=C2=A0relati=
ve to <em>some </em>baseline =E2=80=94=C2=A0improving the environment and c=
apturing carbon and you can sell carbon credits.<a class=3D"footnote-index"=
 href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display:=
 inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> If you buy a million acres of forest and=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>chop do=
wn the trees, as long as you <em>don=E2=80=99t chop them down all at once</=
em>,=C2=A0then you are <em>still</em>, relative to=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>=
baseline, improving the environment and capturing carbon and you can sell c=
arbon credits. Why not!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Even if you <em>do </em>chop down all of the t=
rees, there is still carbon <em>in the trees you chopped down</em>, so rela=
tive to <em>some </em>baseline you are still capturing carbon and can sell =
carbon credits:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Weyerhaeuser produces about 950,000 miles of l=
umber a year and more than enough wood panels to cover Manhattan four sheet=
s thick. Even though lumber doesn=E2=80=99t continue absorbing carbon dioxi=
de, the company takes credit for an additional 11 million tons of carbon he=
ld in those wood products. It reasons that carbon continues to be stored in=
 the lumber after it goes into houses and other structures, which wouldn=E2=
=80=99t be the case if a tree fell and decayed on the forest floor.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Taking credit for carbon in harvested wood, ma=
nufactured products and on timberlands owned by others is inconsistent with=
 guidelines other companies use for their emissions accounting. Ara Erickso=
n, Weyerhaeuser=E2=80=99s vice president of corporate sustainability, said =
the company is pushing its case with the organizations that set carbon stan=
dards.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes! A tree in the forest captures carbon, but=
 it might fall and decay and release that carbon! Better cut it down quickl=
y to prevent that!</p>
