<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a private equity fund and you buy a=
 company and hold it for five years and then sell it at twice the equity va=
luation you paid for it, that=E2=80=99s an annual return of roughly 15%. If=
 your investors wire you the money to buy the company the day you buy it, a=
nd you wire them back the money the day you sell it, then <em>they </em>hav=
e an annual return of 15%; if they evaluate you based on your annual return=
s then you score a 15%. But if they=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>wire y=
ou the money the day you buy the company =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you just float t=
he company for the first, say, year, and only ask them to put up their mone=
y after one year =E2=80=94=C2=A0then their annualized return goes up. Doubl=
ing their money over four years, instead of five, gives them a 19% annual r=
eturn. If they evaluate you based on your annual returns then your score go=
es up.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course you have to find the money to float =
the company for a year. A year ago, though, that was fine! Cash was basical=
ly free! A bank would lend you the money to buy the company, secured by you=
r ability to call capital from your investors, at a very low interest rate.=
 You=E2=80=99d pay a little bit of money to the bank in interest, and get a=
 much better performance for your investors, and they would like you more a=
nd give you more money. Good trade.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, though, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/31207070.258446/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2x=
lcy9iYW5rLXB1bGxiYWNrLWxlYXZlcy1idXlvdXQtZmlybXMtc3RhcnZpbmctZm9yLWJyaWRnZS=
1sb2Fucy03MjZlOTFkZT9tb2Q9aXRwX3dzaiZydT15YWhvbw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb=
6c8119a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;"> not so much</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Reduced bank lending and higher interest rates=
 are chipping away at a practice that investors have complained about for y=
ears: private-equity firms=E2=80=99 use of bridge loans to artificially enh=
ance performance.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nearly all private-equity firms use the loans,=
 called subscription lines of credit or sub lines, to smooth out the proces=
s of buying companies without tapping investors for every deal. But the cre=
dit arrangements have become harder to obtain and much more expensive as ba=
nks have cut lending and interest rates have climbed.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sub lines make it easier for private-equity fi=
rms to do deals. Rather than asking dozens of limited partners to wire cash=
 every time a firm wants to make an acquisition, it can tap a sub line inst=
ead, and only needs to ask investors to send cash every quarter or two. The=
 credit lines allow firms to close transactions quickly and without the ris=
k that a fund investor will forget to send a wire.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This use of sub lines has become standard prac=
tice and that is unlikely to change even if borrowing costs continue to ris=
e, industry observers said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But a more controversial use faces challenges.=
 Buyout firms have discovered that borrowing money for longer=E2=80=94in ef=
fect, drastically postponing the day when they ask investors for money=E2=
=80=94makes paper fund returns look higher by increasing a metric called th=
e internal rate of return. Calculations of IRR depend on the length of time=
 investor money is used to achieve a profit. By using sub lines to reduce t=
his length of time, fund managers can pump up the apparent returns of their=
 funds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now that borrowing costs have risen, though, t=
he artificial boost to a fund=E2=80=99s paper performance might no longer b=
e worth the expense of the loan, said Oliver Gottschalg, a professor at the=
 HEC School of Management in Paris, who studies private equity.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crudely speaking, private equity funds have a =
cost of equity of, say, 15% or 20%, and that cost isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>th=
at=C2=A0</em>sensitive to interest rates. If the cost of debt is 2% and the=
 cost of equity is 20%, borrowing is a great substitute for equity. If thei=
r cost of debt is 7% and the cost of equity is 20%, it=E2=80=99s less good.=
</p>
