<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That said there are some uncertainties:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When is the SEC going to bring a case =
against Coinbase, and exactly what will it say?</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">Will it win in court on its arguments that basically all cryp=
to tokens are securities? Again I think the case is quite strong, but there=
 do seem to be crypto lawyers who disagree with me =E2=80=94=C2=A0including=
 at Coinbase =E2=80=94=C2=A0and eventually judges will decide and there is =
always some uncertainty there.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the biggest uncertainty is, like,=C2=A0is =
this <em>it</em>? Is the SEC=E2=80=99s current posture the final answer on =
US crypto regulation? If we assume that the SEC is going to be maximally ag=
gressive about, not =E2=80=9Cregulating=E2=80=9D crypto, but=C2=A0<em>crack=
ing down=C2=A0</em>on crypto, and if we assume that the SEC will win in cou=
rt because it has a pretty strong case under existing law, then the basic p=
ath for crypto in the US is =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s going to be more or less =
illegal to raise money for a crypto project, or to offer a new crypto token=
 widely, or to operate a crypto exchange that trades anything other than Bi=
tcoin and Ether.=E2=80=9D It will take some time to get there, since the SE=
C moves kinda slowly and the courts move even more slowly and crypto people=
 seem very committed to this bit of complaining about =E2=80=9Cregulatory u=
ncertainty=E2=80=9D rather than =E2=80=9Cthe regulators are clearly and ful=
ly committed to stamping us out.=E2=80=9D But the long-term path that we ar=
e currently on is pretty clear.</p>
